    {
      "id": "2d2dc73a76f0cc2b6bb9b1447b85bf6f1c5b8bc0",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 13:00:32.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nRosso Autotest has started the test process",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "3db7e61521c6f9c248c96c192fa5e1c9e46acc60",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 15:25:39.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\nIt would have been good if this patch was submitted with:\n\n Test-Parameters: testlist=sanity-scrub\n\nso that the correct LFSCK functioning was verified. \n\nTo verify my understanding of this patch - it sets the \"igif_inoi\" (?) flag after a full LFSCK has completed, but only until the next reboot? The \"igif_inoi\" flag is also set in some cases after the initial OI scrub, but it isn't totally clear when that happens - I guess when the initial scrub finds no problems that would require a full scrub (e.g. upgraded filesystem). Having a comment to describe this would have been useful.\n\nIt would have been good to store the \"igif_inoi\" flag permanently (as OBD_FEATURE_COMPAT_NOIGIF for new filesystems or after OI svrub finishes, instead of having to decide this again every time the filesystem is mounted.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "429b3ce6b7ef4b1365adcb0294247afa8a9482d2",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 147,
        "name": "Maloo",
        "email": "maloo@whamcloud.com",
        "username": "maloo",
        "tags": [
          "SERVICE_USER"
        ]
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 16:10:17.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1: Fails\n\nTests received by maloo, run on el6/x86_64, unknown/unknown: (https://maloo.whamcloud.com/test_sessions/e3d2d66a-b40b-11e2-b8f6-52540035b04c).  Ran 1 tests.  1 tests failed: node-provisioning-1.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "e8bb823d045540629d365e32b06fb94233b89af3",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2013-05-03 17:23:28.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 1:\n\n> To verify my understanding of this patch - it sets the \"igif_inoi\" (?) flag after a full LFSCK has completed, but only until the next reboot? The \"igif_inoi\" flag is also set in some cases after the initial OI scrub, but it isn't totally clear when that happens - I guess when the initial scrub finds no problems that would require a full scrub (e.g. upgraded filesystem). Having a comment to describe this would have been useful.\n\nThe \"igif_inoi\" will be set under the following conditions:\n1) for new created filesystem, or\n2) for the device restored after file-level backup, or\n3) for the OI scrub completed the device upgrading.\n\nThe \"set\" can happen during current mount, without restart. Once \"igif_inoi\" is set, then it will not be cleared. Because the IGIF-in-OI is irreversible. \n\n\n> It would have been good to store the \"igif_inoi\" flag permanently (as OBD_FEATURE_COMPAT_NOIGIF for new filesystems or after OI svrub finishes, instead of having to decide this again every time the filesystem is mounted.\n\nWe can add OBD_FEATURE_COMPAT_NOIGIF, but it does not help the code much, because for most of the cases, the \"igif_inoi\" is only set when the device mount, and will not be changed then. It is more convenient/direct for the OSD to check/set \"igif_inoi\" internally.\n\nOn the other hand, both the \"last_rcvd\" and \"oi_scrub\" file can be crashed or lost. For \"last_rcvd\" lost, then \"igif_inoi\" will be cleared, but for the \"oi_scrub\" lost, \"igif_inoi\" will be set. The later one is our expected.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 1
    },
    {
      "id": "b3c99c1ded3da2f1478f7ce2ebb8956517ea8ca9",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
